<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-185-023 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 533 271</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 1 1991 v10 n7 p42(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FBI tests Unix X Window software from Applix. (Asterix integratedsoftware package) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Applix Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Asterix (Integrated software) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionIntegrated SoftwareGraphical User InterfaceWord Processing SoftwareUNIXX Windows (Standard).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FBI Tests Unix X Window Software From ApplixandM;DALLAS -- Applix Inc. has introduced a document preparation package to helpresearchers make the most of Unix workstation graphics and networking.andM;The Westborough, Mass., company introduced the product at Uniforum.andM;Asterix is Unix X Window software that combines an OSF/Motif or Open Lookgraphical user interface, word processing, graphics and a set of macro toolsand spreadsheets into one product, said Cynthia Johnson, the company'sproduct marketing manager for Asterix.andM;Joseph Kielman, chief of the FBI's Research and Development unit, said hisorganization is evaluating the software to help with documentation in supportof the design of electronic systems.andM;The unit is testing Asterix on one of its network of Sun Microsystems Inc.andO;Sun 4 workstations.andP;  Kielman said that if the product works as expected, thebureau might expand it to as many as 25 workstations.andP;  In the future, copiesof the software might be used in select FBI field offices, he said.andM;The Randamp;D unit creates much of the electronic, optical and computer systems theFBI's special agents use in field offices around the country.andM;In support of that development, the Randamp;D unit must prepare a large amount ofpaperwork.andM;&quot;We need to be able to document not only the equipment that we produce, butalso things we are working on, and we are hoping that Asterix will give usthat general technical publishing support,&quot; Kielman said.andM;&quot;We hope it will allow us to be able to do everything from writing boringmemos asking to procure something to writing full technical manuals onequipment that we produce,&quot; Kielman said.andM;&quot;We wanted one overall product that would allow us to work from the Suns andincorporate that into documents and manuals,&quot; he said.andM;The software features live links among all Asterix applications and supportsa variety of import and export formats, Johnson said.andM;Asterix has a set of macro tools including an extension language facilitythat lets users tailor the Asterix software environment to meet specializedneeds.andM;The user can customize the graphical user interface and include data from athird-party database in Asterix documents, Johnson said.andM;Asterix graphics permit users to incorporate illustrations into a textdocument and include facilities for creating, editing, customizing andmanipulating graphics.andM;Optional spreadsheets offer features including interspreadsheet links,projection tables, goal seeking and multiple views of a single spreadsheet.andO;Users can create and customize graphs and charts based on spreadsheet data.andM;Priced between $695 and $995, Asterix is available on Sun Microsystems Inc.'sSparc computers, Digital Equipment Corp.'s DECstation/DECsystem RISCworkstations and X-terminals.andM;Contact Cynthia Johnson of Applix Inc., tel.andP;  508-870-0300.andO;</TEXT></DOC>